I did it! I won!

267
00:11:10.350 --> 00:11:12.545
(Danny)
I won! I won!

268
00:11:12.819 --> 00:11:14.946
What happened?
Are you all right?

269
00:11:15.021 --> 00:11:16.648
Yeah. I’m fine.
Are you okay?

270
00:11:16.723 --> 00:11:18.782
I am the greatest!

271
00:11:19.092 --> 00:11:21.424
The sexy dentist won!

272
00:11:21.794 --> 00:11:23.125
I won!

273
00:11:23.229 --> 00:11:26.926
Danny. you‘re wonderful!
I love you!

274
00:11:27.633 --> 00:11:29.294
[laughing]

275
00:11:30.470 --> 00:11:32.370
[birds chirping]

276
00:11:35.875 --> 00:11:38.639
How. how about Indian food
next time?

277
00:11:38.711 --> 00:11:40.872
We can-- We can make
our own mango chutney.

278
00:11:40.947 --> 00:11:42.574
we can fry a little <i>chapatí.</i>

279
00:11:42.648 --> 00:11:44.172
(Nick)
How about Indonesian?

280
00:11:44.250 --> 00:11:45.774
We could do
a whole rice table.

281
00:11:45.852 --> 00:11:47.183
Oh. yeah.
That will be great.

282
00:11:47.253 --> 00:11:48.413
(Claudia)
I love that.

283
00:11:48.488 --> 00:11:51.048
(Danny)
Wait a minute. Wait a minute.
I think I got it.

284
00:11:51.124 --> 00:11:52.148
What?

285
00:11:52.225 --> 00:11:53.283
It’s 1 :00.

286
00:11:53.359 --> 00:11:54.724
Homemade pasta.

287
00:11:54.794 --> 00:11:55.783
Yeah?

288
00:11:55.862 --> 00:11:57.329
Florentine
Chicken.

289
00:11:57.397 --> 00:11:58.386
Mmm-hmm.

290
00:11:58.965 --> 00:12:00.762
<i>...</i>on a-- on
a bed of spinach.

291
00:12:00.833 --> 00:12:01.857
Oh. yeah.

292
00:12:01.934 --> 00:12:05.734
And a hot antipasto
of mussels

293
00:12:05.805 --> 00:12:07.705
in marinara sauce.
How about that?

294
00:12:07.774 --> 00:12:09.105
[all exclaiming]
Is that good?

295
00:12:09.175 --> 00:12:11.609
Danny. please.
I’m Italian.

296
00:12:12.178 --> 00:12:14.408
Oh. you don‘t think
we can do it. huh?

297
00:12:14.480 --> 00:12:17.005
Didn‘t we make
a great Chinese meal
last night?

298
00:12:17.083 --> 00:12:19.278
Yeah. Well.
look. we‘re not Chinese.
You know?

299
00:12:19.352 --> 00:12:21.582
By us it was Chinese.
What do we know?

300
00:12:21.654 --> 00:12:23.349
[all laughing]

301
00:12:23.423 --> 00:12:24.754
Danny. please.
She‘s Italian.

302
00:12:24.824 --> 00:12:25.916
Yeah.

303
00:12:25.992 --> 00:12:28.017
I can make a better sauce
than your mother.

304
00:12:28.094 --> 00:12:29.322
My poor mother
has arthritis.

305
00:12:29.395 --> 00:12:31.260
Of course you make
a better sauce than her.

306
00:12:31.330 --> 00:12:32.991
Before her arthritis.

307
00:12:33.066 --> 00:12:34.328
[Jack guffawing]

308
00:12:34.400 --> 00:12:37.335
Will you guys shut up?
You‘re depressing the birds.

309
00:12:37.403 --> 00:12:38.392
[laughing]

310
00:12:38.471 --> 00:12:39.529
How‘s your leg?

311
00:12:39.605 --> 00:12:41.004
Oh. fine.

312
00:12:41.074 --> 00:12:43.838
I’ve been banged up so many
times I hardly even notice it.

313
00:12:43.910 --> 00:12:47.038
In college he played
football with a broken wrist

314
00:12:47.113 --> 00:12:49.604
and then two big guys
picked him up

315
00:12:49.682 --> 00:12:50.876
and threw him on his head

316
00:12:50.950 --> 00:12:52.918
and he was unconscious
for three hours.

317
00:12:52.985 --> 00:12:55.249
[exclaims]
Those were the days.

318
00:12:55.321 --> 00:12:56.879
[both laughing]

319
00:12:57.723 --> 00:12:59.054
Hey. Hey.

320
00:12:59.625 --> 00:13:01.991
Listen to the water
lapping against
the sides of the boat.

321
00:13:02.061 --> 00:13:03.358
[sighs]

322
00:13:05.898 --> 00:13:07.627
To be with friends
sipping wine.

323
00:13:07.700 --> 00:13:09.531
this is what it is
to be happy.

324
00:13:09.602 --> 00:13:12.628
This.
and being incredibly rich.

325
00:13:12.939 --> 00:13:14.429
[all laughing]

326
00:13:18.744 --> 00:13:21.474
I’m a lifetime member
of Equitable‘s
Million Dollar Roundtable.

327
00:13:21.547 --> 00:13:22.707
Gimme some cheese.
will you?

328
00:13:22.782 --> 00:13:25.182
I’m one of
the most successful
estate planners in New York.

329
00:13:25.251 --> 00:13:26.912
But that‘s nothing
compared to this.

330
00:13:26.986 --> 00:13:29.352
Nick. please.
I wish that you would relax.

331
00:13:29.422 --> 00:13:31.515
Please.
He‘s always selling.

332
00:13:31.591 --> 00:13:33.218
What are you
talking about?

333
00:13:33.292 --> 00:13:35.021
You‘re an
estate planner?

334
00:13:35.094 --> 00:13:36.322
You‘re an
insurance salesman.

335
00:13:36.395 --> 00:13:37.453
[all giggling]

336
00:13:37.530 --> 00:13:38.690
(Nick)
I don‘t plan estates?

337
00:13:38.764 --> 00:13:40.789
I’m not on
the Million Dollar Roundtable?

338
00:13:40.867 --> 00:13:42.164
Oh. Do you know
what you get

339
00:13:42.235 --> 00:13:44.135
for being in
the Million Dollar Roundtable?

340
00:13:44.203 --> 00:13:45.295
What?
What?

341
00:13:45.371 --> 00:13:47.430
A plastic statue
and a weekend.

342
00:13:47.507 --> 00:13:50.908
a weekend
at the La Cucaracha Hotel
in Puerto Rico.

343
00:13:55.548 --> 00:13:56.640
What are you doing?

344
00:13:56.716 --> 00:13:57.705
[all exclaiming]

345
00:13:57.783 --> 00:13:58.943
I’m gonna make a toast.

346
00:13:59.018 --> 00:14:00.349
Again? Not another one?

347
00:14:00.419 --> 00:14:01.977
Here‘s to us.

348
00:14:02.522 --> 00:14:04.422
Here‘s to apple trees.

349
00:14:05.825 --> 00:14:06.849
to cheese<i>...</i>

350
00:14:06.926 --> 00:14:07.950
Here‘s to cheese?

351
00:14:08.027 --> 00:14:09.085
[all exclaiming]

352
00:14:09.162 --> 00:14:11.562
<i>...</i>and wine and friends
and laughter.

353
00:14:11.631 --> 00:14:12.825
[all laughing]

354
00:14:12.899 --> 00:14:14.025
and life itself.

355
00:14:14.100 --> 00:14:16.125
That‘s beautiful. Sit down.

356
00:14:16.202 --> 00:14:17.294
[all laughing]

357
00:14:17.370 --> 00:14:18.701
Carefully.

358
00:14:20.173 --> 00:14:21.435
[all laughing]
Oh. shit.

359
00:14:21.507 --> 00:14:22.599
(Danny)
What. again?

360
00:14:22.675 --> 00:14:24.472
I don‘t want
this afternoon to disappear

361
00:14:24.544 --> 00:14:26.444
without something
to remember it by.

362
00:14:26.512 --> 00:14:28.742
Some memorial of our
affection for one another.

363
00:14:28.814 --> 00:14:29.838
Yeah. Terrific.

364
00:14:29.916 --> 00:14:31.679
But just don‘t
wave your arms. okay?

365
00:14:31.751 --> 00:14:33.651
This is for all of you

366
00:14:33.719 --> 00:14:35.584
so that we‘ll never forget
this day.

367
00:14:35.655 --> 00:14:37.020
(Nick)
Yeah.

368
00:14:40.760 --> 00:14:42.352
[all screaming]

369
00:14:42.428 --> 00:14:44.396
[all laughing]

370
00:14:44.463 --> 00:14:45.862
I don‘t believe it!

371
00:14:45.932 --> 00:14:47.797
What are you doing
in the lake?

372
00:14:47.867 --> 00:14:49.061
[all screeching]

373
00:14:49.135 --> 00:14:52.298
All right.
I accept that gesture
from my friend.

374
00:14:52.905 --> 00:14:55.430
He‘s not gonna be alone
in doing it.

375
00:14:55.508 --> 00:14:56.532
[all giggling]

376
00:14:56.609 --> 00:14:58.076
My only regret is that

377
00:14:58.144 --> 00:15:01.375
I’m not wearing my $500 suit.

378
00:15:05.418 --> 00:15:07.249
[all screaming]

379
00:15:09.188 --> 00:15:11.554
I’ll just jump in
with my bread.

380
00:15:12.959 --> 00:15:15.086
[all hooting]

381
00:15:20.766 --> 00:15:23.257
[all exclaiming]

382
00:15:38.718 --> 00:15:40.913
[all chattering]

383
00:15:45.224 --> 00:15:47.192
[birds chirping]

384
00:15:51.797 --> 00:15:53.287
(Nick)
Hey. uh<i>...</i>

385
00:15:53.366 --> 00:15:54.765
(Jack)
Hey.

386
00:15:55.901 --> 00:15:57.459
You all right?

387
00:15:57.837 --> 00:15:58.997
Sure.

388
00:15:59.805 --> 00:16:01.602
You look distracted.

389
00:16:02.908 --> 00:16:04.170
I’m okay.

390
00:16:07.146 --> 00:16:08.511
You know.

391
00:16:09.482 --> 00:16:12.383
I think we‘re close enough to
say anything to each other.

392
00:16:14.253 --> 00:16:15.948
Really. Anything.

393
00:16:25.831 --> 00:16:27.298
You and Kate happy?

394
00:16:27.366 --> 00:16:29.095
[branch cracking]

395
00:16:29.602 --> 00:16:31.035
Yeah. Very.

396
00:16:32.672 --> 00:16:34.697
I mean. happy.

397
00:16:34.774 --> 00:16:37.538
Can you honestly say
you‘re really happy?

398
00:16:39.578 --> 00:16:41.671
Yeah. but not
every minute.

399
00:16:42.748 --> 00:16:44.477
It comes in waves.

400
00:16:46.118 --> 00:16:47.278
At times you hit lows

401
00:16:47.353 --> 00:16:49.651
and you can‘t stand things
about each other.

402
00:16:50.289 --> 00:16:53.122
Like the way
her teeth click
when she eats.

403
00:16:53.359 --> 00:16:55.657
The way I smell my sweatshirt
before I put it on.

404
00:16:55.728 --> 00:16:58.253
Sometimes we drive
each other crazy.

405
00:16:59.298 --> 00:17:01.289
And then there are times

406
00:17:01.934 --> 00:17:05.131
we go through a period
like the one we‘re in now.

407
00:17:06.105 --> 00:17:08.039
It comes over us
like an unexpected wave.

408
00:17:08.107 --> 00:17:09.199
puppy love.

409
00:17:10.276 --> 00:17:11.470
I can‘t wait to see her.

410
00:17:11.544 --> 00:17:14.206
And then when I’m with her
my heart beats faster.

411
00:17:16.182 --> 00:17:18.116
I’d expect it
with somebody
who‘s a stranger.

412
00:17:18.184 --> 00:17:20.448
but not somebody
I’ve spent
half my life with.

413
00:17:20.519 --> 00:17:22.111
It’s wonderful.

414
00:17:22.655 --> 00:17:24.088
I wish I could feel that.

415
00:17:24.156 --> 00:17:26.886
Oh. you will.
It‘ll come back.
Just give it time.

416
00:17:26.959 --> 00:17:28.517
No. I’ve never felt it.

417
00:17:36.602 --> 00:17:37.830
[sighs]

418
00:17:37.903 --> 00:17:39.564
I shouldn‘t have
married Anne.

419
00:17:42.675 --> 00:17:44.302
I was crazy as a kid.

420
00:17:44.377 --> 00:17:47.505
I figured
she‘d be some kind of
stability for me.

421
00:17:48.681 --> 00:17:49.978
[snorts]

422
00:17:50.449 --> 00:17:52.679
Well.
she certainly is stable.

423
00:17:54.653 --> 00:17:56.780
I mean. she‘s a decent woman.
she‘s a good mother

424
00:17:56.856 --> 00:17:59.051
but she doesn‘t
do anything.

425
00:17:59.458 --> 00:18:01.016
Doesn‘t think anything.

426
00:18:02.328 --> 00:18:04.353
I’ve never heard
one stimulating idea

427
00:18:04.430 --> 00:18:06.159
come out of her mouth ever.

428
00:18:07.166 --> 00:18:08.861
When she took up photography.

429
00:18:08.934 --> 00:18:11.300
I thought. finally
she‘s gonna do something.

430
00:18:12.171 --> 00:18:15.072
She spent three years
photographing vegetables.

431
00:18:15.141 --> 00:18:16.802
[birds chirping]

432
00:18:17.076 --> 00:18:18.873
She‘s not just stable.
she‘s inert.

433
00:18:18.944 --> 00:18:20.969
So work on it with her.
Talk to her about it.

434
00:18:21.046 --> 00:18:24.277
Jack. I’ve tried for 20 years.
I get nothing.

435
00:18:26.452 --> 00:18:29.353
Do you know how painful it is
to want to love someone?

436
00:18:30.656 --> 00:18:34.490
You‘ve no idea
how lonely I’ve been.

437
00:18:40.800 --> 00:18:42.791
Look at her.
Look at her.

438
00:18:45.104 --> 00:18:46.162
[Nick snorts]

439
00:18:46.238 --> 00:18:48.468
(Nick)
She gets obsessed with that.

440
00:18:48.541 --> 00:18:50.736
She‘ll pace up and down
all day long

441
00:18:50.810 --> 00:18:52.903
with the same thought.
turning it over and over

442
00:18:52.978 --> 00:18:53.910
in her head.

443
00:18:53.979 --> 00:18:56.072
She remembers the day
she got her tooth filled.

444
00:18:56.148 --> 00:18:58.082
Can you remember that?

445
00:18:58.551 --> 00:19:01.611
Christ. I can barely remember
the first time I got laid.

446
00:19:04.190 --> 00:19:05.623
I come home from
a day‘s selling.

447
00:19:05.691 --> 00:19:07.352
she wants to
talk about her work.

448
00:19:07.426 --> 00:19:09.656
Fine. You know what
she talks about?

449
00:19:09.728 --> 00:19:11.161
Vegetables.

450
00:19:11.230 --> 00:19:13.892
For a year and a half
we talked about zucchini.

451
00:19:13.999 --> 00:19:15.899
Then for a year.
green peppers.

452
00:19:15.968 --> 00:19:17.026
That was a nice change.

453
00:19:17.102 --> 00:19:18.399
[laughs]

454
00:19:20.306 --> 00:19:22.797
Last night
was the end of 21 years.

455
00:19:23.876 --> 00:19:25.605
And that‘s enough.

456
00:19:25.978 --> 00:19:27.969
Today‘s the beginning
of a new life for me.

457
00:19:28.047 --> 00:19:29.275
What?

458
00:19:29.748 --> 00:19:31.613
That‘s it. It’s over.

459
00:19:31.851 --> 00:19:33.819
[bird chirping]

460
00:19:34.587 --> 00:19:36.452
You can‘t just quit.
What--what are you<i>...</i>

461
00:19:36.522 --> 00:19:38.990
What are you talking about?
What‘s the matter with you?

462
00:19:39.058 --> 00:19:41.583
I want to make a new start.
I want a new family.

463
00:19:41.660 --> 00:19:43.059
What about your old family?

464
00:19:43.128 --> 00:19:45.460
Lisa‘s 18.
She can handle this.

465
00:19:46.365 --> 00:19:48.856
I want a woman
I can be excited by.

466
00:19:51.437 --> 00:19:53.029
You‘ve got somebody else.
don‘t you?

467
00:19:53.105 --> 00:19:54.732
You got somebody
waiting in the wings.

468
00:19:54.807 --> 00:19:57.537
No. I don‘t.
I swear I don‘t have anybody
waiting in the wings.

469
00:19:57.610 --> 00:19:59.544
Why are you making this
so difficult for me?

470
00:19:59.612 --> 00:20:01.546
I thought
I could tell you anything.

471
00:20:02.648 --> 00:20:04.479
[bird chirping]

472
00:20:07.119 --> 00:20:09.679
How can you
just throw her away
after 21 years like this?

473
00:20:09.755 --> 00:20:11.848
I mean. what is she
supposed to do now?

474
00:20:15.394 --> 00:20:16.656
Oh. boy.

475
00:20:20.332 --> 00:20:22.926
I thought if I told you.
you‘d be happy for me.

476
00:20:23.536 --> 00:20:26.266
I even had this fantasy that
you‘d handle the divorce.

477
00:20:28.040 --> 00:20:30.372
That I would handle
the divorce?

478
00:20:31.777 --> 00:20:33.711
In the first place.
I’m not a divorce lawyer

479
00:20:33.779 --> 00:20:36.077
and if I were.
I’d probably represent Anne.

480
00:20:36.849 --> 00:20:38.714
I can‘t believe
you would do this.

481
00:20:38.784 --> 00:20:40.308
Jack. please.

482
00:20:41.587 --> 00:20:44.613
This is the hardest thing
I’ve ever gone through
in my life.

483
00:20:47.993 --> 00:20:49.824
All right. I’m sorry.

484
00:20:55.501 --> 00:20:58.527
Oh. God.
Nick. this is awful. Jesus.

485
00:21:09.582 --> 00:21:11.277
Come on. let‘s go.

486
00:21:11.617 --> 00:21:13.517
[all chattering]

487
00:21:15.054 --> 00:21:16.487
Want some more of these?

488
00:21:16.555 --> 00:21:18.523
Oh. yes. Thank you.
Good. good.

489
00:21:20.359 --> 00:21:23.328
You know.
beans are very much
misunderstood.

490
00:21:23.395 --> 00:21:26.091
They have a complex set
of amino acids.

491
00:21:26.899 --> 00:21:29.026
lf you eat beans
together with rice.

492
00:21:29.101 --> 00:21:30.625
you never have to
eat meat.

493
00:21:30.703 --> 00:21:32.898
Danny loves to
talk about beans.

494
00:21:32.972 --> 00:21:35.065
Go ahead. sweetheart.
Talk.

495
00:21:35.474 --> 00:21:37.999
It’s the combination
that counts.
Here. you want some of these?

496
00:21:38.077 --> 00:21:39.101
(Nick)
Yeah. I do.

497
00:21:39.178 --> 00:21:40.907
You know. I’ve been
thinking about that.

498
00:21:40.980 --> 00:21:42.140
(Jack)
About what?

499
00:21:42.214 --> 00:21:44.182
Photographing vegetables
in combinations.

500
00:21:44.249 --> 00:21:46.843
not just one at a time.
You know?

501
00:21:49.054 --> 00:21:50.453
[stammers]

502
00:21:50.756 --> 00:21:52.223
I’m not sure yet.

503
00:21:54.727 --> 00:21:57.389
(Kate)
Hey. I did some research
on sailboats for the summer.

504
00:21:57.463 --> 00:21:58.521
(Danny)
That‘s great.

505
00:21:58.597 --> 00:21:59.655
